  <div id="grooming" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Grooming a White Silky Coat in Our Humid Climate" imageAlt="Maltese puppy having its face gently wiped during grooming and tear-stain care" imageSrc={malteseGrooming} imagePosition="left">
      <p>The Maltese coat is silky and single-layered: it sheds very little, which means it needs your help instead of dropping on its own. Brush 3 to 4 times a week to prevent matting, and book professional grooming every 6 to 8 weeks. Most Singapore owners keep a short "puppy cut", which turns the show-ring coat into a genuinely easy-care one, and it looks adorable.</p>
      <p>Tear staining is the Maltese-specific one. Reddish-brown marks under the eyes show clearly on a white coat. A daily wipe with clean water, keeping the face hair trimmed, and steady grooming keep it in check. The brush and grooming tools you need are already in the starter kit.</p>
    </CaptionedBlock>
  </div>

  <CloudDivider fillClass="fill-[var(--color-mint-100)]" />
  <div id="health" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Maltese Health: What We Check Before You Take One Home" imageAlt="Maltese puppy at a veterinary health check before going home" imageSrc={malteseVet} variant="mid">
      <p>Every Maltese goes home vet-checked, vaccinated, dewormed, and microchipped. The Maltese health points worth knowing are a small few: patellar luxation, a kneecap issue common to toy breeds; dental crowding, because a small jaw leaves little room for teeth, so the oral care items in your kit matter; and tear staining, which is cosmetic and manageable. We say this once, plainly, so you hear it from your seller and not from a forum later.</p>
      <p>Feeding is simple: your puppy comes with the small-breed food it is already eating, and any change should be gradual over a week. Tiny puppies also need regular meals to keep blood sugar steady, one more reason we don't sell to the "teacup" label. For portioning guidance see the puppy health checks explained guide.</p>
    </CaptionedBlock>
  </div>
  <CloudDivider fillClass="fill-[var(--color-mint-100)]" flip />

  <div class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="The Truth About Teacup and Micro Maltese" imagePosition="none" variant="card">
      <p>The Maltese is the breed the "teacup" label targets hardest, because it is already tiny. You will see "teacup," "micro," and "smallest in Singapore" Maltese listings, often at a premium. We don't sell to that label. Dogs bred to be unusually tiny carry higher risks: fragile bones, dental and breathing problems, low blood sugar, and shorter lives.</p>
      <p>A healthy Maltese at 3 to 4 kg is already one of the smallest, most flat-friendly dogs you can own. If a seller promises a size below that and guarantees it, treat the promise as a warning, not a feature.</p>
      <div slot="side" class="clay h-full bg-[var(--color-peach-100)] p-6 sm:p-8">
        <p class="text-xs font-bold uppercase text-[var(--color-cream-500)]" style="letter-spacing: 0.08em;">Teacup red flags</p>
        <ul class="mt-4 space-y-3">
          {[
            'Guaranteed adult weight below 3 kg',
            'No mention of the parents\' actual size',
            '"Teacup" or "micro" priced at a premium',
          ].map((fact) => (
            <li class="flex items-start gap-2.5 text-sm leading-relaxed text-[var(--color-cream-700)]">
              <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="3" class="mt-0.5 shrink-0 text-[var(--color-coral-500)]" aria-hidden="true">
                <path d="M18 6 6 18M6 6l12 12" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" />
              </svg>
              {fact}
            </li>
          ))}
        </ul>
      </div>
    </CaptionedBlock>

    <PawTrail bg="bg-[var(--color-surface)]" colorClass="text-[var(--color-coral-300)]" />
  </div>

  <CaptionedBlock heading="Your Maltese's First Week at Home" imageAlt="Maltese puppy settling into a set-up playpen during its first week home" imageSrc={malteseSettling} imagePosition="left">
    <p>Day 0: we deliver, free, at a time that suits you, usually morning or evening. The playpen, bed, water, and toys are set up before your Maltese explores the room, and we walk you through all 30+ starter-kit items in person. Learn more about how our free home delivery and setup works.</p>
    <p>Days 1 to 3: keep it calm and close. Maltese settle fastest with gentle company nearby, a fixed feeding routine, and the toilet pads where we placed them. Some night whimpering is normal adjustment.</p>
    <p>Days 4 to 7: the routine sticks. This is the window to book your free first lesson with an AVS-certified trainer; see what the free AVS-certified training lesson covers. For anything in between, you WhatsApp us.</p>
  </CaptionedBlock>

  <div id="reviews" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <Carousel
